<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-762-584  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 762 584.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Industrial Computing  April 1989 p31(3).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>How to ask 'what-if?'andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Lawrence, Andrew.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Simulation software generates functional models of processes orobjects on a computer, and enables users to ask 'what if'questions.andP;  Uses of simulation in manufacturing includeengineering modelling, robot and machine tool simulation, andshort term production planning.andP;  A computerized simulation isfaster and less expensive than the real thing, and inexpensivepersonal computers have revolutionized the use of simulationsoftware.andP;  Entry level PC shop floor scheduling software is pricedfrom about 4,500 pounds sterling, while most leading systems costbetween 10,000 and 30,000 pounds sterling.andP;  The best knownsimulation software on the market includes Witness from IstelAutomation, Hocus from PE Consultants, Genetic Planning Board fromInsight International, and Schedule X from Hewlett-Packard.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     MicrocomputersSoftware PackagesManufacturingSimulationApplicationsCost.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>